issue.title: Improve documentation of BECOME_ALLOW_SAME_USER

labels.name: has_pr
labels.description: This issue has an associated PR.

issue.body:
https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/reference_appendices/config.html#become-allow-same-user

The documentation of BECOME_ALLOW_SAME_USER is quite ambiguous. 
> This setting controls if become is skipped when remote user and become user are the same.

Does setting it to true, or to false, skip it? It can be read as "allowing to become the same user", or "allowing to run `become` on the same user".

> If executable, it will be run and the resulting stdout will be used as the password.

If *what* is executable? Can you set BECOME_ALLOW_SAME_USER to a file path pointing to an executable file? The next part seems to say no: `Type: boolean`

issue.title: Remove unused argument in call to CLI.build_vault_ids

labels.name: stale_review
labels.description: Updates were made after the last review and the last review is more than 7 days old.

labels.name: needs_verified
labels.description: This issue needs to be verified/reproduced by maintainer

issue.body:
I saw the todo on setup_vault_secrets about removing unused arguments and decided to tackle it.

I can't say I have completely removed the unused argument in build_vault_ids, though, because I started worrying that some unknown code outside of __init__ could be relying on its presence in the signature.  As a result, I am not going to remove it in this commit, but work needs to be done here to figure out if anything or anybody is using build_vault_ids and relying on `create_new_password` being present in the signature.

##### SUMMARY

<!--- Describe the change below, including rationale and design decisions -->
Removed a line in `CLI.setup_vault_secrets` that sent a value to a now unused argument in `CLI.build_vault_ids.` I chickened out on removing the unused argument in `build_vault_ids`'s signature because I don't know whether any other code, internal to this project or externally, implicitly relies on `create_new_password` being in the signature.  If whoever reviews this wants me to remove the argument, I will be happy to do so.

comment.body:
I have now deprecated the passing in of `create_new_password` to `build-vault-ids`.  I have also removed tests in the test suite that were pointless due to `create_new_password` no longer being used.

That being said, I am unsure what to make of the failure of Sanity Test 2, due to the unhelpful output of `Bash exited with code '1'.` I would like some help figuring out what this means so I can fix the problem.

+    # TODO: verify that nothing else is passing an argument to

+    # external code depends on create_new_password being part of the signature,

commits.message:
Add support for TLS 1.3 Post Handshake Auth (#82063)

TLS 1.3 adds a different method it can use to request a client
certificate after the handshake but Python does not allow this by
default. This commit sets the attribute needed to enable this scenario
when using client certificates on Python 3.8+, 3.7.1+.

pull_request.title: Add support for TLS 1.3 Post Handshake Auth
pull_request.body:
##### SUMMARY
TLS 1.3 adds a different method it can use to request a client certificate after the handshake but Python does not allow this by default. This commit sets the attribute needed to enable this scenario when using client certificates on Python 3.8+.

Fixes: https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/81782

##### ISSUE TYPE
- Feature Pull Request
